0":"1290","1304":"1304","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","22 April 1295":"22 april 1295","after 1297":"na 1297","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ormesby, Yorkshire, England":"Ormesby, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1281–after 11 September 1342":"about 1281–after 11 September 1342","1281–1342":"1281–1342","1285–1315":"1285–1315","1281–Female":"1281–Deceased","1284–1297":"1284–1297","1309–Female":"1309–Deceased","1304–1359":"1304–1359","1231–1295":"1231–1295","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","about 1281":"about 1281","after 11 September 1342":"after 11 September 1342","1231":"1231","1297":"1297","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1304":"1304","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","22 April 1295":"22 April 1295","after 1297":"after 1297","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Ormesby, Yorkshire, England":"Ormesby, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Percy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","nickname from Old French <i>percehaie</i> ‘pierce hedge’ (Old French <i>percer</i> ‘to pierce, penetrate’ + <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, fence’), perhaps with the sense of someone breaking into an enclosure. <i>Percehaie</i> is the name of one of the sons of the foxes Renart and Hermeline in the medieval French epic <i>Roman de Renart</i>, whose earliest known version is from the 1170s. The surname is older than that, but it may originate in a nickname for the fox as ‘enclosure piercer’, perhaps amounting to ‘chicken thief’.","habitational name from any of several places called Percy in Calvados, Eure, and Manche; William <i>de Perci</i>, the Domesday tenant-in-chief and under-tenant of Hugh, Earl of Chester, came from either Percy-en-Auge (Eure) or Percy (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Piercey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Piercy","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcey","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Peercy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":9,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":34,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":47,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":56,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Alexander de Percy was born about 1281, in Ormesby, Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir William de Percy III, Lord of Ormsby, was 52 and his mother, Johanna Neville, was 22. He married Mrs. Alexander Percy. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 11 September 1342, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1281–after 11 September 1342":"umbes 1281–pärast 11. septembrit 1342","1281–1342":"1281–1342","1285–1315":"1285–1315","1281–Female":"1281–Surnud","1284–1297":"1284–1297","1309–Female":"1309–Surnud","1304–1359":"1304–1359","1231–1295":"1231–1295","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","about 1281":"umbes 1281","after 11 September 1342":"pärast 11. septembrit 1342","1231":"1231","1297":"1297","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1304":"1304","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1315":"1315","1279":"12